The '''International Spiritualist Federation''' is a society dedicated to supporting [[spiritualist]] churches around the globe, with particular emphasis on those based in countries which do not support spiritualism as a religion.<ref name="harper">{{Cite encyclopedia  | title = International Spiritualist Federation [ISF]  | encyclopedia = Element Encyclopedia of the Psychic World  | volume = 10  | pages = 330–331  | publisher = Harper Collins  | date =   | id =   | accessdate = September 23, 2011}}</ref> The federation was first proposed at an 1888 conference held in [[Barcelona]],<ref name="harper"/> but was officially established in 1923. Every year since then they have run courses and held lectures for one week which attempt to raise awareness of spiritualism. Particularly notable was the 1925 conference attended by then head of the organisation, [[Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]],<ref name="Times">{{Cite news   | last = Brown  | first = David  | coauthors =   | title = Spiritualist world splits over failure to expel charismatic healer who raped his patients  | newspaper = The Times  | location =  | pages = 11  | publisher =   | date = July 4, 2008  }}</ref> who blamed [[ectoplasm (paranormal)|ectoplasm]] for his faulty slides during his presentation.<ref>{{Cite news   | last =   | first =   | coauthors =   | title = IN OUR PAGES: 100, 75 AND 50 YEARS AGO; 1925:Pesky Spirits  | newspaper = International Herald Tribune  | location =  | pages = 8  | publisher =  | date = September 7, 2000  }}</ref>

