{{Infobox saint | name = Our Lady of Itatí | image = Virgen de itati 3.jpg | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | titles = Patroness of Corrientes | venerated_in = [[Roman Catholic Church]] | major_shrine = [[Basilica of Our Lady of Itatí]], [[Itatí, Corrientes|Itatí]], [[Argentina]] | feast_day = [[9 July]] | attributes = [[Blessed Virgin Mary|Statue of the Virgin Mary]] in prayer, blue embroidered mantle, solar crown, veil | patronage = [[Corrientes Province]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Corrientes]] }} '''Our Lady of Itatí''' ({{lang-es|Nuestra Señora de Itatí}}), also known as the '''Virgin of Itatí''', is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[Titles of Mary|title]] of the [[Virgin Mary]], whose principal shrine is in the city of [[Itatí, Corrientes|Itatí]], [[Corrientes Province]], [[Argentina]]. Her feast day is celebrated on July 9, with an anniversary celebration on July 16.
==History== [[File:Basílica Itatí.jpg|thumb|Basilica of Our Lady of Itatí]] According to legend, the wooden representation of the Virgin Mary saved the life of 17th-century [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] missionary, Luis de Bolaños, known for his attempts to convert the natives to Catholicism. It is also said that the Virgin intervened in a battle between two native tribes, resulting in the victory of the tribe with the conquerors' aid.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Dazzling Face of Our Lady of Itati|url=http://en.mariedenazareth.com/une-minute-avec-marie/dazzling-face-our-lady-itati}}</ref>
On July 16, 1900, the statue of Our Lady was granted a [[Canonical Coronation]] under the pontificate of [[Pope Leo XIII]], who proclaimed the statue as the patron saint of Corrientes. In 1950, a [[basilica]] to enshrine the image was built with one of the tallest domes in [[South America]], now known as one of the largest Catholic pilgrimage sites in Argentina, where draws about 300,000 pilgrims annually.<ref>{{cite web|title=Catholic News Agency|url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/marian-celebration-draws-hundreds-of-thousands-to-argentina/}}</ref>
