'''Viśiṣṭacāritra''' or '''Bodhisattva Superior Practices''' ([[Sanskrit|Skt]]; {{cjkv|c=上行|p=Shàngxíng}}, [[Japanese language|Japanese]]: ''Jōgyō''), is a [[bodhisattva]] mentioned in the 15th, 21st, and 22nd chapters of the ''[[Lotus Sutra]]''. He is one of the [[Bodhisattvas of the Earth | four great perfected bodhisattvas]] who attends [[Gautama Buddha]] and protects the ''Lotus Sutra'' and its devotees.<ref name="Kato">{{harvnb|Kato|1993|p=372}}</ref> The other three are [[Anantacaritra]], [[Visuddhacaritra]], and [[Supratisthitacaritra]]; together they make up the four great primarily evolved bodhisattvas.<ref name="Kato"/><ref name=Reeves>{{harvnb|Reeves|2008|p=280}}</ref>  Viśiṣṭacāritra is also believed to represent the "true self" characteristic of [[buddhahood]], which is the selflessness of [[Nirvana]].<ref name="McCormick">[http://nichirenscoffeehouse.net/ShuteiMandala/4bodhisattvas.html McCormick, Ryuei M. "The Bodhisattvas of the Earth" ''Nichirenscoffeehouse.net''. Nichiren's Coffeehouse and Gohonzon Gallery, 2002. Web. 21 Feb. 2011.]</ref>

== In Nichiren Buddhism ==
In most schools of [[Nichiren Buddhism]], [[Nichiren]] is believed to have fulfilled the vow of Viśiṣṭacāritra during his lifetime.<ref name="McCormick"/> This is because he revealed what he held to be the Superior Practice of chanting the title (''daimoku'') of the ''Lotus Sutra'', [[Namu Myōhō Renge Kyō]], which would quickly allow all beings to attain enlightenment in their present lifetime, no matter what their capacities. According to Anesaki, from the time of his exile to [[Sado, Niigata|Sado Island]] Nichiren deemed himself as the reincarnation of Viśiṣṭacāritra.<ref name="Anesaki 1916">{{cite book|last1=Anesaki|first1=Masaharu|title=Nichiren, the Buddhist Prophet|date=1916|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge, MA|isbn=9781498186582|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=Ub0KAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&output=reader&hl=en&pg=63|quote=This is the first definite statement' about his personal connection with Viśiṣṭacāritra (Jap. Jogyo), the leader of the saints called out of earth in the chapter on the 'Apparition of the Heavenly Shrine.' From this time on, Nichiren remained constant in the belief that his former life was that of Viśiṣṭacāritra, although he often referred to other saints as his predecessors, and spoke as if he were a reincarnation of one of them.}}</ref> 

===Nichiren Shōshū, Soka Gakkai and Kempon Hokke===
In [[Nichiren Shōshū]], [[Soka Gakkai]] and the [[Kempon Hokke]] schools, Nichiren is revered as the reincarnation of Viśiṣṭacāritra<ref name="nst.org">{{cite web|title=About Nichiren Shoshu Buddhism|url=http://www.nst.org/an-introduction-to-nichiren-shoshu-buddhism/|publisher=Nichiren Shoshu Temple}}</ref> because he revealed the "cause" of [[Buddhahood]]: chanting "[[Namu Myōhō Renge Kyō]]", a practice called ''daimoku'', whereas Gautama is seen as the "Buddha of True Effect" as he only revealed the "effect" of Buddhahood.<ref name="nst.org"/> This is based on the passage in Chapter 16 of the ''Lotus Sutra'' that reads, "Originally I [Shakyamuni Buddha] practiced the bodhisattva way, and the life that I acquired then has yet to come to an end"<ref name="truebuddha">{{cite web|title='True Buddha'|url=http://www.sgilibrary.org/search_dict.php|publisher=Soka Gakkai Dictionary of Buddhism}}</ref> Nichiren Shōshū and [[Soka Gakkai]] interpret the passage to mean that Gautama Buddha must have practiced something to attain Buddhahood, but in the ''Lotus Sutra'' he did not reveal what that practice was, whereas Nichiren taught the daimoku, which leads all beings to Buddhahood.

These groups conclude [[Shakyamuni]] Buddha attained buddhahood in the remote past through the daimoku.<ref name="truebuddha"/> ''The Object of Devotion for Observing the Mind'' states, "Showing profound compassion for those unable to comprehend the gem of the doctrine of three thousand realms in a single moment of life, the Buddha wrapped it within the five characters [of Myōhō Renge Kyō], with which he then adorned the necks of the ignorant people of the latter age."<ref>{{cite book|last=Daishonin |first=Nichiren|authorlink=Nichiren|title=The Writings of Nichiren Daishonin|url=http://www.sgilibrary.org/view.php?page=376&m=0&q=| pages=376|publisher=Soka Gakkai|isbn=9784412010246}}</ref>

